text: ah hi everyone vocal fry here the
internet's busiest music nerd and it's
time for a review of the new polo g
project hall of fame this is the newest
album from
chicago singer rapper songwriter
2020 double xl freshman polo g a year
later following up his breakthrough
project the goat where he brought a lot
of heart competent singing and
tragic storytelling to this current
mellow trap wave
sure the production did have some
blemishes and the tracklist overall was
a bit samey but all this was mostly made
up for with pology's incredible
sincerity
when he approaches topics like drugs
violence
street life family ptsd now he had some
big singles in the lead up to hall of
fame that i wasn't too crazy about but
i was still hoping the overall
experience of this project would
outweigh whatever one or two tracks i
wasn't crazy about however after having
run through it i find hall of fame to be
a difficult project to sum up
because it's pretty bloated and
lackluster in pockets too
this thing is not nearly as trim as the
goat at 20 tracks in 54 minutes
and there are numerous songs on this
thing that either don't seem necessary
or
don't entirely work like on gnf where
pology tries some excessive aggression
on for size to the point where he's not
really on tempo as much as he typically
is
which in my opinion is not a lane he
operates in convincingly
there's also the mild losses featuring
young thug that doesn't
have the bite you expect a thugger track
to have and why are we getting this
loose
zooted freestyle when the tracklist is
already so padded out
for the love of new york with nicki
minaj is a difficult listen
mostly because this track is a very
trashy synth-heavy piece of pop rap
looking to
work its way into some kind of vaguely
tropical playlist
but broken guitars is maybe the toughest
listen that there is on this project
the track features these awful distorted
droning guitar chords in the background
it's like this painful attempt at a
hip-hop rock fusion polo tries to
wail his way into a soaring lead vocal
but crashes and burns for the most part
as much as i respect the sentiment of
the track but at least
many of these tracks are admirable
attempts at not making another
one-dimensional record
we have the song so real which is a
passionate song
from polo g to his significant other a
track that's profoundly wholehearted in
its own way especially as pology says
love you like my first gun plus the
acoustic guitars on this track bring it
almost into like a country wrap
territory
there is a drill cut on this lp2
featuring fabio foreign as well as pop
smoke that
goes over really well even if he isn't
necessarily the focal point of the track
with him
appearing in the second half but truth
be told when hall of fame is at its best
it's when it feels like a cleaner bolder
leaner
more cleanly assembled version of some
of the tracks off of the goat
which is really most of the tracks on
the front end like painting pictures
toxic epidemic boom polo g also finds
some fantastically explosive chemistry
with g
herbo on go part one and heart of a
giant proves just how much polo and rod
wave are kindred spirits as they trade
melodic verses over these kind of creaky
piano leads
there's not a section of this record
where there aren't highlights
i was even pleasantly surprised by the
track featuring kid leroy where
it's one of his best sung choruses
legitimately there's also the
devastating portrayal of
a friend dying on the track bloody
canvas polo really does save his most
impactful lyricism for last on this one
look most of the time on this project
the quality
is there just as it was on the goat this
is the same polo g that showed so much
potential
on that project now trying to capitalize
on it but
faltering much of the time with some
lackluster features
and style switch ups that go over pretty
awkward overall i liked hall of fame
it's a more ambitious project than the
goat but not quite as consistent
but i think if you whittled this thing
down to its best tracks
it would be one of the most impressive
rap projects of the year
now even though i'm not crazy about this
thing i wouldn't count pology out
he wouldn't be the first young artist to
blow up and then try to go big on his
next project with more tracks
bigger guests cleaner production more
changes in style
other artists who have found themselves
in similar positions
have gone on to have lengthy careers i
guess all i can hope for is a more
focused project
next time around and i will leave it at
that feeling a decent two strong six
